title: Iserlohn
description: The city of Iserlohn is located at edge of the wooded, hilly Sauerland area southeast of Dortmund in the German state of North Rhine-Westphalia. Documented in the 11th century, it received its town charter in 1237. In medieval times it was famous as producer of light metalware and armor. The community suffered from a large-scale fire in 1712 and a rebellion in 1849. Of its historic structures, there remains the 11th-century St. Pankratius Church and the 1350 Oberste Stadtkitche. Today the city is an industrial center, producing machinery, chemicals, rubber, leather, and metal products. The 2004 population estimate was 98,800.

title: Düsseldorf
description: The northwestern German city of Düsseldorf is situated on both banks of the Rhine river some 21 miles northwest of Cologne. Known from at least 1159, it received its charter in 1288. It served as the capital of the duchies of Berg and Jülich from 1511 until it came under the Palatine-Neuberg line of rulers in 1609. It went to Prussia in 1815, and developed considerably in the 1870s as iron and steel industries and various commercial activities established themselves. World War II caused heavy damage to the city, but much of its historic architecture has been restored and much new development undertaken, notably the famous shopping street called the Königsallee. Restored historic structures include the 13th-14th-century St. Lambertuskirche, whose crooked tower has become the town symbol, the old town hall of 1567-1588, the tower of the castle of the electors palatine, built 1752-1763, Benrath Castle built 1755-1773 by Nicolas de Pigage, and the ruins of the palace of Frederick I Barbarossa. The first German skyscraper, the Wilhelm-Marx-Haus was built herein 1924. The city is a cultural center, housing a museum of ceramics, the state museum, and the city library, which features a collection of works by and about the poet Heinrich Heine, born in Düsseldorf. The city is a hub for transportation and communications, with an airport and three harbors. Economic activities include commerce and banking, and the manufacture of glass, chemicals, iron, steel, and textiles. The estimated population for 2004 was 572,900.

title: Cuilcagh
description: The mountain of Cuilcagh rises on the border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland. Its lower slopes contain many caves and the Northern Ireland side in County Fermanagh encompasses the famous Marble Arch Caves. The mountain is also the site of the Cuilcagh Mountain Park, created in 1999 with the main purpose of conserving the unique blanket bog area on the mountain. The area attracts international tourism, and was designated a European Geopark in February 2002.
